<P><i></i></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR=#dcdeed><TD NOWRAP width=20% valign=top align=left><B><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2><A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/umimiraesyri.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mimir Aesyri</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif BORDER=0 WIDTH=10 HEIGHT=10></FONT></B><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Registered User</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>posts: </FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>3</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#333333>4/12/01</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#333333>12:24:39 pm</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT><BR><img src=http://209.15.79.25/bbu/avatar/Some_Guy_4.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif">&nbsp<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Re: SOTS, KEG, Public - Community effort. Need input </font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">The thing is, the &quot;public&quot; system won't work well on a server like ours.  Why?  Because on Zeb, the uber raids are all based on who gets there first.  If you can mass the people and organization it takes to own a zone or uber mob first, then chances are you will get it.  However, most larger guilds are also flexible, and have several alternate targets in mind in case the first spot they are interested in is taken.<br>
<br>
In the past (on E'ci anyway) the public usually attempted to reserve a zone or mob in advance, and then would complain if they didn't get it.  On Zeb a reservation system will likely NOT be respected, at least not unless all the guilds sign off on the idea, and I doubt they will.  All zones and mobs will remain FFA regardless.  Hopefully that same failed reservation system and the complaints that accompanied it will not be taking root here.<br>
<br>
Now, if a public raid can be organized quickly and get a full raid party into the zone early enough to pre-empt anybody else who also has designs on the zone, then there probably won't be a problem.  If not, they may end up sharing the zone, or being forced to look elsewhere, like the other guilds do when something they plan on is taken.<br>
<br>
My advice to any public raid leader would be to be prepared to lead your group into battle somewhere, but don't count on it being the first place on the list.  Have several alternates in case the first spot is taken or empty, and have the people ready to move to whichever one is open as quickly as possible.  Make sure your followers have as much varied resist gear as they can so they can tailor it to whatever ends up being the final target.<br>
